{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_basil_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517170835/1945081601/0455.xml":{"full_text":"NATIONAL\nJaps May Get a Democracy\nBut Not for Many Years\nWill Have to Be Educated From Ground Up Before\nVote Would Mean Anything\nWashington, Aug. 11-\u2014(AP) \u2014If Ja\npan surrenders, the allies may force\nrevision of the .lapSfieae constitution\nto give the people an Immediate voice\nin government.\nThis developed today as one of the\nlikely key points in a long-planned\ncampaign to bring democracy to the\nJapanese. The campaign would be\nlaunched as soon as allied forces oc\ncupy the islands.\nBuilt around the pledges of the\nPotsdam surrender ultimatum, an in-1\ntensive drive would be carried on to I\nprepare the Japanese for something;\nthey never have done before in their I\nhistory determine for themselves\ntheir own form of government.\n\u201cBy Freely Expressed Will\u201d\nToday's allied prbposal of terms\nupon which a Japanese surrender i\nwould be accepted specified that in\naccordance with the Potsdam declara\ntion the ultimate form of govern\nment in the nation shall \u201cbe estab\nlished by the freely expressed will of\n,ihe Japanese people.\"\nGovernment officials here say that\nto accomplish these objectives the\nJapanese will have to be educated\nfrom the ground up.\nThese officials cautioned against\nholding an election too early. They\nsay a plebiscite need not necessarily\nbe linked to occupation, since the al\nlies could supervise an election even\nafter external control over Japan is I\nsubstituted for the direct controls!\nrepresented by troops.\nin the meantime, however, the su-\u25a0\npreme allied commander who actually I\ndirects the government through the\nemperor under the big four's terms\nwill be in a position to force imme\ndiate constitutional changes.\nJapan's constitution was handed\ndown to the people by the emperor\nin 1890. It can't be changed except by I\nthe emperor. The emperor carefully j\nkept most of the power for himself, j\nCan Dissolve Diet\nFor instance, whenever the House\not Representatives of the Diet dis\nagrees with the cabinet, the emperor\ncan dissolve the legislative body. If\nthe House falls to pass the budget\nhis cabinet demands, the previous\nyear's budget goes into effect with\nany additions upon which the minis\nters may decide.\nOne of the first moves of the allies\nmay be to force Hirohito\u2014or his son.\nAkihito, if he succeeds to the throne\n\u2014to turn the purse strings over to\nthe lower House. This House's mem\nbers are elected on a fairly represent\native basis by the males of Japan who\nhave had universal suffrage sinco\n1928.\nThe emperor may find taken away\nfrom him his power to dissolve the\nparliamentary body and to issue in its\nabsence ordinances with the effect of\nlaws. His cabinet thus may be forced\nto abide by majority decisions ot the\nHouse or resign.\nMilitarists to Get. Out ___\nThe emperor probably would be re\nquired to replace with civilians the\narmy and navy officers who have\nbeen the only ones eligible under the\nconstitution for ministers ot war and\nmarine.\nAlong with these steps Hirohito\nWould be forced to provide, under the\nterms of the Potsdam ultimatum, for\n\"freedom of speech, of religion, and\nof thought, as well as respect for\nfundamental human rights.\u201d\nAt the same time he would have to\nremove the obstacles, placed in 1930\n\u2022when the army began to tighten its\nhold around the throne, on the demo\ncratic elements which then were be\nginning to show\u2019 some strength in the\ncountry. These included many Japa\nnese educated In the United States,\nsmall businessmen, students and\nChristians.\nMany officials here feel that only\nafter all of these precautions have\nbeen taken and the Japanese have\nbeen educated in the workings of de\nmocracy, perhaps for years, can a\nrepresentative plebiscite he held on\ntheir form of government.\nFREED OFFICERS\nMAY BE RECALLED\nEnlisted Men Discharged by\nWay of Point System Will\nBe Out of Mufti Only if\nThey Volunteer\nWashington, Aug. 12 (AP) \u2014Th^\nwar department said today that sol\ndiers discharged under the point sys\ntem will not he called for further\nservice unless they volunieer. Outlin\ning its policy on relnduction, the de\npartment also said:\u2014\n1. Officers released under honor\nable conditions will be placed on in\nactive status, subject to recall if their\nservices are needed In that status,\nthey are not liable to induction under\nselective service.\n2. Officers and enlisted men dis\ncharged under other than honorable\nconditions are separated completely\nfrom military service and placed un\nder jurisdiction of selective service.\nThey are eligible for induction, how\never, onlj\u2019 if the war department\ngrants a waiver of the other than\nhonorable discharge.\nThese waivers, the department said,\nare based on review of the- individ\nual's records including the reason for\ndischarge, previous military service\nand potential future use to the army.\n3. Enlisted men who are discharged\nfor physical disability, dependency or\nfor the national Interest may be rein\nducted if the conditions under which\nthey were released change subse\nquently. However, selective service\nboards take into consideration the\nlength of prior military service.\n\u201cIt is not the desire or, intent of\nselective service or the war depart\nment to reinduct former members of\nthe armed forces who have had long\nand honorable service, unless they\nvolunteer for further service,\" the\ndepartment said\nPlanes Six Miles Above Earth\nMay Broadcast Television, FM\nNew York, Aug 9\u2014(>-?)\u2014A sys\ntem of broadcasting television and\nFM programs the length and breadth\nof the United States by means of air\nplanes cruising six miles above the\nearth was announced today by Weet\ninghouse Electric corporation.\nThis system, known as stratovision,\nwould make coast-to-coast television\nand FM broadcasting possible \u201cat a\nreasonable cost\" even to the most\nIsolated farm home \"years ahead of\na any previously suggested system.\"\nWalter Evnns, Westinghouse vice\npresident. told a luncheon of writers\nand editors.\nOriginated by C. E. Nobles, 27, of\nU. S. OFFERS JAPS\nSHIP TO REPLACE\nONE HIT IN ERROR\nNot Indemnity but Attempt\nto Resume Relief Service\u2014\nJaps Must Accept Several\nConditions\ni Washington. Aug. 8 (AP)\nThe United States offered today to\ntransfer to the Japanese government\nja ehip similar to the relief vessel\nAwa Maru, sunk by an American\nsubmarine several months ago.\nThe state department said the offer\nof transfer of the ship was not to\nbe construed as an indemnification;\nfor the Awa Maru, which it has pro\nposed to discuss after the war ends.\nCarried Relief Supplies\nThe Japanese relief vessel, which!\nhad been carrying supplies to allied,\nnationals in Japanese custody was\nsunk by mistake by an American\nsubmarine while returning from a'\n(voyage to Hong Kong and Singapore.\nOn that voyage it carried relief sup\nplies furnished by the allied gov\njernments for allied prisoners of war\n(and civilian internees of the Japa\ni nese.\nThe American government offered\nto transfer a vessel of approximately\nthe same size and characteristics If\nthe Japanese met several conditions.\nThese included operation between\nJapanese-controled territory to a\ntransfer point in the Pacific for the\nexchange of Japanese and allied civil\nians, seriously sick and seriously\nwounded prisoners of war and \u201csur\nplus protected personnel.\u201d\nThe state department said the\nJapanese would have to agree to pick i\nup at the transfer point relief sup\nplies for and mail for allied prisoners\nstill held by them. In return the'\nUnited States would pick up similar;\nsupplies and mail for Japanese pris-i\noners.\nI The Japanese would be required to\nj report proposed movements of the\n(ship seven days in advance.\nThe vessel which the United Stales\niwae prepared to transfer to Japan\n'has a gross tonnage of 11,758. carries\nj 2500 passengers and has a speed of\n'l7 knots.\nDEGAULLEOFFRANCE\nAT CAPITAL SOON\nTO MEET TRUMAN\nGermany\u2019s Western Bound\ni ary, French Fate m Indo-\nChma Are Matters Apt to\nBe Discussed\nWashington. Aug. 13\u2014(AP)\u2014Gen\nCharles DeGaulle w ill reach Wash\nington on the 22d to meet President\nTruman. Four subjects vital to\nFrance\u2019s future may come before\nthem.\nj The White House announced today\nthe trip of the president of the pro\nvisional government of France is\ndefinite, without discussing its pur\npose beyond \"the mutual desire of\nthe two men to meet\nLikely Topics\nAmerican and French sources,\nspeculating questions likely to be\nbrought up, gave attention to these\ntopics:\n1. The French economic situation.\n2. The question of Germany\u2019s west\nern boundary.\n3. France's share in German rep\narations.\n4. The Far Eastern situation, es\npecially as respecting Frenah terri\ntory.\nDe Gaulle may stress particularly\nI the materials France needs to restore\nher industry and agriculture to full\nscale operation. France already has\nbeen allocated 400.000 tons of Ameri\ncan coal per month if shipping is\navailable, machine tools, agricultural\nequipment and. of course, food, and\nother products are likely to rate top\npriority on DeGaulle's list.\nThe French point out that Ger\nmany's eastern boundary was fixed at\nPotsdam, but that French questions\nI regarding the Rhineland and the\nRuhr have gone unanswered to date,\nj The French are concerned about this\ni first of all because of its security\naspects. It is obvious, however, that\njif France were permitted to exact\nsufficient reparations in kind from\nthese German industrial centers, the\nI security problem would be solved al\ni tomatically.\nI In the Far East, the French had\nhoped their troops might liberate\nIndo-Chlna from the Japanese. Now\nthat the war seems likely to end be\nfore such an expedition can be under\ntaken. the French are wondering how\nquickly the other major allies will\npermit restoration to France of what\nformerly was an important part of\nits empire.\nProbably more important than any\ndetails the two leadsr bring up in\ntheir discussions will lie how they get\nalong personally. It can have im\nportant bearing on postwar relations\nof the two nations.\nHome for Atomic Bomb\nTakes Toll of 39 Lives\nOak Ridge. Tenn., Aug. 13\u2014(AP)\u2014\nClinton engineer works, home of the\natomic bomb, was built at a cost of\n39 lives, j. r. Maddy, district Mkfety\nengineer, announced.\nHe eaid 33 lives were lost in con\nstruction and six in operational ac\ncldentti. and that the death rate was\nless than half that on comparable\nconstruction jobs\nParis, Tex., etratovlsion was said to\nconquer \"the astronomical expendi\ntures which have hampered all ear\nlier concepts of nation-wide television\nservice.\" Evans, who said applica\ntion had been made with the Federal\nCommunications commission for teat\nflights this fall, explained:\n\u201cTelevision and FM radio waves\ntravel tn a straight line and for all\npractical purposes stop at the hori\nzon. This means that television\nbroadcasts front the highest practi\ncal tower erected on the ground can-,\nnot be received much more than 90.\nmiles away.\nTHE SPRINGFIELD WEEKLY REPUBLICAN: SPRINGFIELD, MASS.: THURSDAY, AUGUST 16, 1945\nMILLION YANKS\nMAY BE NEEDED\nTO PATROL JAPAN\nArmy Expects to Move in\nRight After Surrender\nTroops May Occupy Seven\nLeading Nip Cities\nWashington, Aug. 10\u2014(AP) \u2014More\nthan a million Americans may be re\nquired for the immediate occupation\nof Japan once the Japanese surren\nder is final.\nHigh government officials saiA to\nday United States forces unquestion\nably will have to move in first tq\ndisarm and police the Japanese home\nislands. Russian troops probably will\ntake over in Manchuria, Korea and\nthe island of Sakhalin, which they\nhave shared with the Japanese.\n.MacArthur\u2019s Troops First\nThe Potsdam surrender ultimatum\nof July 26 said key points in Japan\nwould be held until its war-making\npower is destroyed and the terms of\nthe United States-British-Chinese 1943\nCairo declaration for the dismember\nment of the empire are carried out.\nBecause they are closest to the\nmain islands, troops under Gen Doug\nlas MacArthur, with some marine and\nnaval detachments, are expected to\nmake up the original occupation\nforce.\nIf present plans are followed these\ntroops probably will occuply seven of\nJapan's principal cities, maintaining\nonly normal control over the rural\nareas.\nThe formal arrangements for the\nmore permanent control of Japan still\nare a big three secret, but the spec\nulation here is that individual Japa\nnese islands may be assigned later\nfor occupation by the United States,\nGreat Britain, China and Russia.\nEmperor and His Powers\nIf Emperor Hirohito is allowed to\nstay, the expectation is the alites\nwould merely step into the place\nwhich has been occupiel by Japa\nnese army leaders in recent years,\nlaying their orders before the em\nperor for his automatic signature.\nTn such event the form of sover\neignty exercised by the emperor\nwould be followed, with the allies ac\ntually ruling Japan just as they rule\nGermany. This route could be used\nto carry out the objectives laid down\nin the Potsdam surrender ultimatum\nwhich the Japanese say they are\ni willing to accept.\nThese terms were in an eight\npoint program, summarized as fol\nlows:\u2014\n1. Elimination for all time of the\nauthority and influence \u201cof those who\ni have deceived and misled the people\nof Japan into embarking on world\nconquests.\"\n2. Occupation of key points in\nJapanese territory until a new order\nof peace, security and justice is es\ntablished.\n3. Limitation under the Cairo dec\nlaration of Japanese sovereignty to\nthe islands of Honshu, Hokkaido,\nKyushu. Shikoku and such minor is\nlands as the victors later designate.\n4. Complete disarmament of Japa\nnese military forces and their re\nturn to their homes.\n5. Removal by the Japanese gov\nernment of all obstacles to the\nstrengthening of democratic tenden\ncies among its people, including free\ndom of speech, religion, thought and\nrespect for human rights. War crimi\nnals are to be dealt stern justice,\nbut the Japanese would not be en\n-1 slaved as a race or destroyed as a\nnation.\n6. Permission for Japan to main\ni tain industries sustaining her econ\nomy and permitting payments of rep\narations in kind, but not those en\n(abling her to rearm for war. Access.\nbut not control of, raw materials\nwould be permitted with the Japa\nnese eventually returning to world\ntrade.\nI 7. Withdrawal of occupation forces\nwhen these objectives have been\nreached and a peaceable and respon\nsible government established with the\nfreely expressed will of the Japanese\npeople.\n8. Provision for proper and ade\nj quate assurances of good faith in the\nsurrender of all Japanese armed\nforces.\nThe Cairo declaration made more\nspecific reference to the partitioning\nof the Japanese empire. It was .sub\nscribed to by the late President\nRoosevelt, former Prime Minister\nChurchill and Generalissimo Chiang\nKai-shek.\nThe three leaders agreed at that,\ntime Japan shall be stripped of\u2019all\nPacific islands she has seized nr oc\ncupied since the beginning of World\nwar 1 in 1914. All territories stolen\nfrom the Chinese, such as Manchu\nria, Formosa and the Pescadores,\nwould be restored to China.\nJapan would be expelled from all\nterritories she has taken by violence\nand greed. Korea would become free\nand independent \u201cin due course.\u201d\nSOCIAL SECURITY\nASSISTS 4,250,000\n1 7.\nThat Many Receiving Bene\nfits at End of Program\u2019s\nFirst Decade\u2014Mr Truman\nBooster for It\nWashington, Aug. 13\u2014(API\u2014The\nsocial security program wound up its\nfirst 10 years tonight with a report\nthat 4.250.000 persons are now receiv\ning benefits.\nAnd from President Trunran came\na statement that he will make specific\nrecommendations to Congress\" to make\nft \u201ca more perfect instrument for the\nmaintenance of economic security\nthroughout this country.\u201d\nIn the past decade. Mr Truman said,\nsocial security has become an es\ni sential part of the American way of\nlife. Through it assistance is provided\ni for the aged, for people left dependent\nIby the death of workers and for un\nemployment Insurance.\n\"Social^ security worthy of the\nname.\" he declared. \u201cIs not a dole or\nla device for giving everybody some\nthing tor nothing. True social se\nleurlty must consist of rights that are\nI earned rights\u2014guaranteed by the law\nof the land.\nI \u201cOnly that kind of social security\nis worthy of the men and women\nwho have fought and are now fighting\nto preserve the heritage of America.\u2019\u2019\nAs of August 1. Chairman Arthur\nJ. Altmeyer of the Social Security\nboard, said in the agency's 10th an\nnual report, approximately 190.000\npersons were receiving weekly unem\nployment compensation payments,\ntwice as many as on V-Eday. Benefits\naveiaged 418 a week, he said.\nAll told. 4.250,000 men. women and\nchildren now are receiving cash bene\nfits aggregating 1111,000,000 a month\nunder the five social security pro\ngrams\u2014old-age and survivors insur\nance, state-federal programs of public\nassistance to the needy aged, depend\nent children and blind.\nSince the act went into effect Au.\nI gust 24, 1935. social security payments\nhave approximated 19.000,000,000.\nPortland, Or., Testing Spot\nFor Nation\u2019s Racial Problem\nNegro Population Has Increased 1000 Per Cent in Four\nYears, With Result Demand for Equal Rights Has\nArisen\nPortland, Ore.. Aug. 11 \u2014(AP) \u2014The\nPacific Northwest, where a Negro\nminority has increased 1000 per cent\nin four years, is becoming a testing\nground for the nation's racial prob\nlem. There were only 2000 Negroes\nin the Portland area before the war\nand the problem\u2014ls there was a prob\nlem\u2014was not so urgent as to demand\nsolution. But today 20,000 Negroes\nare seeking what they believe to he\ntheir rights and are insisting that\nthe whites do something.\nThe Negroes are not alone in that\nviewpoint. The city club* including.\nPortland's top business and profes\nsional men, made an extensive survey\nand the investigating committee came\nback with a strongly-worded report\nurging 'more rights for the Negro.\nSome see the situation as an op\nportunity. \u201cThe Northwest has as\nyet set no rigid patterns in its social\nan<i economic treatment of minority\nraces,\" A. A. Liveright, executive\ndirector of the American council on\nrace relations, told a Portland audi\nence. \u201cYou have an opportunity to\nset a pace good or bad for the\nfuture.'\nConditions haven't reached a boil\ning point. \u201cNone of us wants any\ntrouble,\" says William McClendon,\neditor of a Negro newspaper. But\nthere have been traces of trouble:\nKights in busses, brawls in taverns,\nintemperate talk. Things like these\nkeep cropping up:\nA shipyard's tinhatter hears a city\nofficial declare publicly there won\u2019t\nbe jobs for any of nearby Vancouver's\n18000 Negroes once peace comes, and\nsays \"I'm sure not gonha take it\nlying down.\"\nA Negro clergyman\u2019s wife, refused\nservice in three restaurants, asks,\n\"Don\u2019t the white people see the bit\nterness they're creating?\"\nMcClendon explains this way: \u201cYou\ncan\u2019t oppress one tenth of your popu\nlation forever without driving at\ni least, some of them to the breaking\nj point. The Negro soldier who\u2019s been\nfighting for democracy abroad is\ngoing to rome back demanding de\nmocracy at home. And if he doesn\u2019t,\n[get it \u2014well, he's steeled to bloodshed\nnow.\"\nThe war influx\u2014proportionately\nlargest of any Pacific coast area\u2014\nhad two effects: It solidified Negroes'\ndemands for rights accorded other\nI citizens; and it stirred racial antag\nonism. An occasional demand came\nfor segregated schools. A teacher\nwho had lived for years in the same\ndistrict with a Negro family suddenly\ngot up a petition to oust them.\n\"Every time the Negro people ask\nfor their full share in American de\nmocracy. a problem is created.'' com\nmented Edwin C. Berry, secretary of\nthe Portland Urban league and a\nNegro. \u201cSome people think the only\nway to solve the problem is to force\nthe Negroes back into the lowly place\nto which white society has assigned\nthem. That way lies in danger.\"\nTwo New Elements Produced\nIn Making the Atomic Bomb\nNeptunium No 93 and Plutonium No 94 Were Made in\nTiny Quantities\nI Washington. Aug. 11\u2014(AP)\u2014Sc\u2019en\ntists produced two new elements in\nI making the atomic bomb and gambled\nor. their knowledge of less than a\nmilligram of one of them to help\nmake the missile an enemy city-\u2019\n(Smashing success.\nThe two new elements are nep\nitunium. No 93, and plutonium. No 94.\n\u25a0which have been added to the pre-\u2019\nviously known 92 elements of varie\nties of matter. The two are derived\nifrom uranium.\nProduction of the new elements\nwas disclosed In a scientific review,\n\u25a0released by the war department, of\nexperiments leading up to final pro\nduction of the atomic bombs loosed,\non Japan. Many of the details still\nare clouded in military secrecy.\nLexington Given Beauty Treatment\nAfter Two Years Fighting Japan\n\nShe s Been Hit Twice While Destroying 862 Planes and\n306,075 Tons of Shipping\nBremerton, Wash.. April 23\u2014(AP)\n(Delayed! The \"Big L.\" the queen\nof the aircraft carriers, the Lexing\ni ton, snuggled in a drydock at the\nI Puget sound navy yard today enjoy\nling the oceanic equivalent of a beauty\n(treatment after two years of uealing\ndeath to the men of Nippon and\nfighting oft their replies in kind.\nShe has taken two hits\u2014a torpedo\noff Kwajalein and a suicide plane\u2019s\nflaming crash dive last year off the\nPhilippines. She has sailed within\n.68 miles from Toklo and sent her\nI planes in to lash the Japanese.\n\"And to think,\u2019\u2019 said Capt Thomas\niH. Robbins, her skipper, I had to\nLome here to get a leaky deck.\"\nMd Planes Destroyed\nl The captain, whose home is in\n(Washington, D. C.. paused a moment\n(in relating the story of the \"Big L\"\nto glare at the ceiling where ham-\nI mers whanged. A couple of pans\nfrom the galley were on the floor to\ncatch the drops. Reporters here for'\nthe first civilian inspection of a war\ntime overhaul at Bremerton grinned\nand the skipper went back to his\nstatistics.\nThe ship\u2019s own guns have knocked\ndown 15 planes, but her aircraft have\nsmashed 372 in the air and erased 475\n(on the ground. The \"Big Ls pilots\n\u25a0have sent to the bottom 300.075 tons\njof enemy \u2019shipping, damaged another\n568.320 tons and assisted in the sink-\nIng of four enemy aircraft carriers.\nThe Lex has steamed nearly 160,000\n(mllyd aim? she was placed In com\nmission February 17, 1943. Once she\nreturned to Bremerton \u2014to have that\ntorpedo damage cleaned up. Damage\nfrom the suicide plane attack, which\n(caused 110 casualties, was repaired\noft Luzon.\nJ The skipper paused in the telling\n\u201cGo grab some men.\" he said. \"L\n'don\u2019t care who you grab. I don\u2019t care\nwhat they say. They may tell you\nthe ship stinks Go see the blue\njackets. They have the heart and\n'soul and life of the ship.\u201d\nThe reporters went out among the\n(2000-odd crew members and picked at\n'random and tound none who said the\nI ship stinks. Mostly they colled heh\n(with a touch of reverence. The Lex.\u201d'\nand to some she was The Old Girl.\"\nThere was Joe Mann of North\nI Tazewell. Va who lost a buddy when\nthe suicide plane crashed into the\n(carrier's Island. Joe. seaman (1c)\nlikes to fire five-inchers at Japanese\nplanes.\n1 Rubin Borah of Brooklyn, boat-\nSome white businessmen hope the\nNegroes will end the problem by re\nturning whence they came. But they\nadd that the Negroes probably won't\nThe history of past migrations and\ncurrent surveys both indicate that\nj most newcomers, come shipyards or\nsoup lines, are here to stay.\nHow have the Negroes been received\nhere? In the shipyards, they insist\nthey have to fight for skilled jobs.\nThe AFL boilermakers union still ad\nmits Negroes only to auxiliary mem\nbership. Very few* have obtained jobs\nin permanent, industry.\nThe Kaiser yards, which employed\n9000 Negroes at peak, hold special\nracial induction classes \u201cWe explain\n;to the new white workers that we\u2019re\nall in this war together and have to\nwork together.\" said Jane Martin,\nwoman's assistant personnel manager\nat Oregon shipbuilding corporation.\nOf course, there are elbow rubs, but\nin general the two races get along\nbeautifully.\"\nWhat Negroes Sre Asking\nInvestigators say they want these\nthings, in this order: (1) An equal\nchance; (2) decent homes without\nconfinement to a fixed district; (3)\nthe right to enter any restaurant,\ntheater or other public facility: (4)\nto associate, without criticism, with\nanyone who wants to associate with\nthem.\nWe're not asking that you admit,\ndrunks to the best restaurant or dis-1\norderly residents into exclusive sub-'\nurbs.\u201d said Kenneth Smith, director\nof the Negro USO. Bur. there are\nplenty of drunk, disreputable white\npeople whom you wouldn\u2019t want.\nthere, either. What w* ask is simply\nthis: That a man be judged by char\nacter, not by color.\u201d\n.That' about social equality and in\nt^rmamage? The question angers;\nNegro leadens.\n\u201cIntermarriage. intermarriage\nthat's all anybody tells you when you\u25a0\nask for a decent job,\u2019\u2019 a Negro burner\ntold questioning white coworkers.'\n\u201cWill you tell me how my holding a\njob as e burner could possibly force!\nany white girl to marry me\u2019\"\nNegro leaders point oi t that inter\nmarriage is as taboo generally among\u25a0\nNegroes as whites, and that personal!\nrelationships\u2014unlike the right tn ear,\nin a restaurant \u2014can\u2019t be established\nby passing a rule.\nPortland is doing nothing as yet.\nofficially. But dozens of church and\ncivic groups have set up interracial\nchoirs, meetings, churches. The city\nI club committee\u2019s report recommend\ned an educational program, a labor-,\nmanagement policy of hiring and pro- i\nmoting all races strictly according to\nability, opening of hotels and restau\nrants to all races.\nWhite businessmen in the newly\nformed Portland urban league whose\npurpose is integration of Negroes into\nj the community, are planning a mass\njob hunt for Negroes whose shipyard\n'jobs are due to disappear.\nThe element plutonium is so rare\ni that at the end of 1942 only 500\nI!micrograms of pure plutonium salts\ni had been produced. And that is just\na little less, the army estimated, than\nj would be needed tn make the head\njof a pin. (A milligram is nne-thou\nsandth of a gram and a micrograin\nis cne-millionth.)\nAnd it was on the knowledge of\nplutonium \"gleaned from less than a\nI milligram\" of it that the government\n!decided to go ahead with a plant in\nWashington state for the production\nand separation on a large scale of\nflthe metal which can be used tn ex\nplode the atomic bomb.\n1| Both plutonium and U-235, another\nI uranium product, can be utilized to\n\u2022effect the explosion.\nswain's mate (2c). who weighs 225\npounds, was playing rummy when\ngeneral quarters sounded.\nHe said: \u201cWe hit the gun and had\n'it loaded, cocked and firing in half a\n'second flat. We had it firing before\n'(the gong stopped. One of the planes\ncame right in at my quad Every,\ni barrel was firing. The Jap plane ex\nploded in a big ball of flame and\nlanded 25 feet down tn front of us\n\"1 think our quad got him.\"\nThere were no heroics in their d\n(voices. Lieut Bartholomew C. Thibo-\ndean of San Francisco hadn't met'\nanybody, he said, who wasn't scared\n(\"But you get used to it, and every-,\n[body does his job.\"\nChief Water Tender Kenneth H.\nMorse of Solana Beach, Cal remem\nbered that Capt (now rear-admiral):\nFelix B. Stump was in command\nwhen the Lex took the torpedo off\nKwajalein. They were praying for\nthe moon to go down, when about\nSO planes came in. The guns of the\n\"Big L\" scored their first kill by\ndowning th er, put in Lieut Kenneth\nL. Johnson of Seattle. Rut one tor\npedo reached the Lexington.\n\"I'll never forget the orders from\n(Capt Stump.\" said Morse. \"He told\nus: Don't worry\u2014l\u2019ll do the worry\ning.\u2019 That made us feel a lot better,\neven though we were out of control\ntor half an hour.\"\nSome of the -boys were \"plank\nowners\" crewmen who had been\naboard since the Lex was commis\nsioned. There are 29 officers and 570\nenlisted men in this group Since\nthey've been with her the Old Girl\nhas crossed the International dateline\nseven times and the equator 22 times\ntaken 18.98 S plane landings served\nher crew 3,729,182 meals.\nCapt Robbins put omphalic rm-\nI Pharis to the suggestion of pride in\nthe talk of the crew\n\"1 say I think this is the finest\nship In the American navy, if not in\nany navy.\" said the skipper. \"It's\nthe finest from the bottom deck to\nthe bridge I only came ibov.d In\nJanmirv. My contribution to the ship\nIs just a trifle. What it ,s I found\n\u25a0on arriving aboard.\n\"The Lexington has been m 90 per\n(cent of the navy's battles in the past\nyear.\"\nBy the time this reaches print the\ndrip pans will be oft the captain's floor\nand the Lex and her brew will be\n'hack in the navy's liattlos. her flight\ndesk as warm with activity and hei\niguns ready. I\nFBI CHIEF FEARS\nWAVE OF CRIME\nAFTER WAR ENDS\nJ. Edgar Hoover Notes In\ncreasing Juvenile Offenses\n\u2014Prges Economic Stabil\nity, Strong Law Enforce\nment\nBy FRANK I. WELLER\nWashington, Aug. 11 \u2014(APj\u2014J. Ed\ngar Hoover is afraid that there's go\ning to be a postwar crime wave.\nLast year an estimated 1.393,663\nmajor crimes were committed, one\nevery 22 second*. FBl's file of crimi\nnal records has jumped to 60,000,000.\nOne. out. of every 22 persons in the\nnation has been fingerprinted in con\nnection with some major crime. More\nthan 80.000 are being sought a* fu\ngitives.\nThe chief G-man says he kept hie\nfears to himself at first lest they\nbreak down confince in our total war\neffort on the home front And he had\nhoped that our common danger from\nthe enemy would discourage lawless\nness.\nIt didn't work\u2019 that way.\n\u201cFun\" is the excuse given police by\nthe alarming number of teen-age\n\u201cdelinquents\" for their criminal acts.\nWhen they were asked whether they\ndidn't know they couldn't get away\nwith it. they replied.\u2014\n\u201cIt was fun. so what?\u201d\nMany Youngsters\nYouths under 21 totaled 22 per cent\nof th(k>e taken in custody by FBI last\nyear. For the first time, says Hoover,\nthese young toughies seemed utterly\nindifferent to punishment. He didn't\nfully grasp the significance until 12-\nmonth reports were in. and he had\nbefore him a summary of similar ex\nperience by local police.\nNow* he is concerned that in these\n\u201cjuvenile delinquents\" there is crop\nping up a postwar source of hardened\nadult criminals. There are enough of\nthe oldsters already.\nConvictions for bank robbery rose\nin 1944 from 29 to 53; for then from\ninterstate shipment from 668 to\n1426; theft of government property,\n1143 to 1815 (only 643 in 1943); frauds\nagainst the government, 235 to 348\nand there were 34 kidnaping\nconvictions\u2019\nThese items, especially the kidnap\nings, lead Hoover to believe the time\nhas come to quit hoping for the best\nand warn the public:\n\u2018Our nation must be careful not to\nrepeat the errors which brought\nabout the tragic aftermath of World\nwar 1 and its two decades of lawless\nness. There may well be a repetition\nof this national disgrace follow ing the\npresent war unless we are alert to\ncur civic and moral responsibilities.\"\nTwo Determining Factor*\nThe FBI chief keeps strictly out\nof politics, but he says:\n\u201cTwo factors are going to be im\nportant in determining the extent of\npostwar crime: (1) The degree of\neconomic stability and (2) the com\nparative strength of American law\nenforcement.\"\nBy the la\u2019ter he means that there\nwill not be enough police to handle\npostwar crime if the nation again\ncommits the errors that made possi\nble the rich and powerful \u201cBooze\u201d\nand \"snatch\u201d rackets.\nBut it is the first\u2014economic sta\nbility that worries Hoover for\nthe moment.\nWe now are producing for the\nwhole world. America alone cannot ab\nj sorb thp peacetime product? Even\nwith high individual purchasing pow\nier of these plants working at\nfull blast. If they do not continue\nworking at full blast, where are the\npeople now working in them to find\njobs?\nHoover's observation is simplicity\nitself. \u2018ldle hands made mis\nchief.\"\nAnd this time we have coming\nback into civilian life a great mili\ntary force which has been the best\npaid. best-fed. best-clothed the world\never has known. Thousands have\nbeen accustomed for the first time\nto eat and live and spend far above\nthe level they once knew. A gener\nous government has seen that their\nfamilies left at home lived better, too.\nIt might be harder, this time, for\nthem to submit to impoverishment\nand despair in a postwar depression\nwithout protest and perhaps violence.\nHoover is not beating the drums\nof disaster. He is simply trying to\nlook ahead at the possibilities in the\nG-man's everlasting struggle with\ncrime.\nSOLONS TO TACKLE\nIDLENESS THREAT\nSenate Group to Renew\nHearings the 21st On Full\nEmployment Bill' Com\npensation On Docket\nWashington. Aug. 13 \u2014(AP)\u2014Sen-\nate committee hearings on the top\npostwar question of jobs and jobless\nness were scheduled today in the first\ndefinite move toward reconvening\nCongress early next month.\nA banking subcommittee will re\nsume hearings August 21 on a sweep\ning economic measure called by its\nauthors \u201cthe full employment bill.\"\nThe finance committee is expected to\nmeet August 29 on expansion of the\nunemployment compensation system\nwith maximum benefits nf $25 a week\nfor 26 weeks.\nCongress itself will convene prob-j\nably on September 4 or 5 Senate Ma\njority Leader Barkley has announced.\nThe plan is to process the most-*\nneeded pieces of legislation through,\ncommittees before that time Then\nthe lawmakers could begin consider\ning them on the floor immediately\nupon their return from their bob-\ntailed vacation The recess originally\nhad been slated to last until Oe\ntoher 8.\nCommittee action had nor been\nscheduled today on three other legis\nlative items Barkley put on his high\npriority list.\nThose include bills to authorize the\nPresident to reorganize the executive\ndepartment, to create a surplus-prop\nerty disposal system headed by one,\nman rather than a board as at pres\nent. and consideration of which war\ntime boards and agencies should be\nabolished and w hi. h continued when\npeace returns.\nMembers of the House ways and\nmeans committee, which will consider\nthe unemployment compensation\nmeasure, are expected to begin com\ning back next week, although no\nhearings of any kind have been an\nnounced on the House side.\nChairman Doughton (D-NC) said\ntoday he doubted the ways and means\ngroups could have new social security j\nlegislation ready for Congress by Sep\ntember 4.\nSome of the few lawmakers who\nstayed here are pessimistic about the\nchance of getting much work done\nbefore late fall. Several of the ineas-\nurea in Barkley s program are con\ntroversial.\n\nU. S. Sub Makes Surface Raid\nOn Jap Convoy, Gets 4 Ships\nGrowler, Now Missing in Action, Took Part in Fight\nUnique in Submarine Warfare\nGIRL ARMY FLIER\nKILLED IN CRASH\nAT BENNINGTON\nElizabeth Everett, Former\nWASP, and Lieut Robert\nLancaster, Released Pris\noner, Crushed at Airport\nBennington, Vt., Aug. 13\u2014Miss\nElizabeth Grace Everett. 24. daughter\nof Mrs Grace Burnap Everett and the\nlate Edward H. Everett of Bennina\nton. and Lieut Robert Lancaster, 23.\nUSAAF. pilot of a B-17. son of Mr\nand Mrs Elmer Lancaster of Wash\nington, D C., were instantly killed at\nabout 12 30 p. m. today when the\ncivil air patrol plane the latter was\nl piloting crashed at the local airport.\nThe plane was owned by Aram Dl\ncranian. Bennington CAP pilot.\nWitnesses were the sister of Miss\nEverett. Miss Sarah Everett. Mrs\nLuther R. Graves and a guest of Mrs\nGraves. They reported to airport au\nthorities tha\u2019 the plane went into a\nspin and plunged downward, hitting\nthe field at the northwest end.\nDr John D Lane, town health offi\ncer. ordered the removal of the bodies\nfrom the plan' Miss Everetts bodv\nwas taken to Havnes Kane funeral\nhome. Elm street, and will be moved\nto the Everett home. Lieut Lancas\nter's body is to be sent to Washing\nton tomorrow.\nMiss Everett was a graduate of\nVassar college and the first woman\nservice pilot from Bennington, having\nwon her silver wings at Avenger field,\ni Sweetwater. Tex., on May 23. 1944.\n\\fter the, WASPS were disbanded, she\nhad been a flying instructor and in\nrecent months liad been at York. Pa\nin this capacity. She was on a leave\nof absence from this fleld and had\nexpected to return there in October.\nLieut Lancaster was a veteran of\nthe 3th air force. He returned to\nthis country after V-E day. having\nbeen a prisoner in Germany for sev\neral months. He was a graduate of\nHotchkiss school in Lakeville. Ct., and\nattended the University of Pennsyl\nvania before enlisting In the air\ncorps in 1943 Besides his parents, he\nleaves a brother in the navy V-12 at\nHarvard university: a sister in\nWashington, and a great-aunt. Miss\nAnna Kaltenhack. Arlington. Vt.\nInvestigation of the crash is being\nmade by State Inspector Edward\nKnapp and the Bennington airport\ncommission, of which Lieut Lee C.\nWarner CAP and Motor Vehicle\nOfficer Kenneth J Fletcher of Ben\nnington are members.\n\u2018GAS\u2019 RESTRICTION\nTO END FEW WEEKS\nAFTER JAPAN QUITS\nBan On Travel Wjll Ease\nWithin Few Months\u2014\u2018Or\nderly\u2019'Reconversion Being\nMapped\nWashington Aug. 10 (AP)\nGovernment officials forecast today\nthat gasoline rationing will end with\nin a few weeks after Japan folds.\nThey eald travel restrictions would\nease in a few months.\nStirred into feverish action by the\nJapanese surrender broadcast. lead\ners of th* various agencies concerned\nwith steering the e'onomy from war\nJo peace met in hurriedly-called con\nferences.\nControl Removal Planned\nThe sessions dealt with the tre\nmeudous problem of releasing indus\ntry from munitions production now\nbooming at the rate of $45.000.000.000\na year, and with manpower, ration\n\u2022ing, price and travel restrictions.\nI The draft situation was unchanged\nfor the moment, pending official de\ntermination of the date the war shall\nend. That is when the draft stops.\nAt the White House War Mobtl\nizer John W Snyder who also has\nthe job of reconversion director con\nferred with War Production Board\nChairman J A Krug and approved\nWPBs emergency program for sn\n'orderly and simple removal of as\nmany industrial controls as possible\nwhen the war ends.\nKrug tentatively scheduled a news\nconference for tomorrow morning to\ndiscuss the reconversion outlook gen\nerally but his aids said the detailed\nprogram would not be ready for an\nnouneenien' before Monday at the\nearliest. This is to give other gov\nernment agencies iffected by it a\nchance to make suggestions\nA high WPB official described the\nplan as \"sound, simple and clear,\" and\none that will do the joh of leading\nindustry to a goal set by President\nTruman unprecedented civilian\ngoods production.\nSenator Langer Eager\nTo Halt Military Draft\nWashington. Xug. 13\u2014(AF\u2019\n-tor Langer iR-ND) announced today\nthat, as soon as Congress reconvenes\nnext month, he will introduce legisla\ntion to put an immediate halt to the\ndrafting of men\nThe measure, he said, also will pro\nvide that \u201cthose already inductea who\nha\\e not been sent abroad shall be\nreturned to their homes and that those\non furlough not be sent, back over\nseas.\"\nVictory Won't, Automatically,\nBring U. S. Draft to an End\nWiihintK\u2019n. Aug. 10\u2014 1 AP>\u2014 End\ning of th* drift depends ftr\u00bbt on Ja\npan second on President Truman,\nand third on the Congress.\nToday, the army was standinj on\nthe statement of Secretary of War\nStimson: It will not reduce its forces\n\"by even one man\" below the num\nber it believes necessary to defeat\n\u25a0lapan. And. In the light of today's\ndevelopment, selective service of\nficials pointed out that even victory\nwill not. of Itself, bring the draft end.\nThe law provides that selective serv\nice (a* far as its draft duties are\nconcerned) shall expire on the date\nof the termination of hostilities in the\npresent war or on such earlier date\nas may be specified.\nI The termination oX ho\u00bbUUUe\u00ab must\nNATIONAL\n7\nWashington, Aug. 11\u2014(AP)\u2014Th*\nUnited States submarine Growler, now\nmissing in action, once made a bold\nsurface attack on a Japanese convoy\nand torpedoed two destroyers and two\nmerchant ships.\nThe incident, which Rear-Admiral\nRalph Waldo Christie called \"unique\nin submarine warfare was related\nby the navy today in a general ac\ncount, of five days of operations by\nfive submarines during which at least\n10 enemy ships, including a 22,500-\nton aircraft carrier, were sunk and\n159 British and Australian prisoner*\nof war were rescued. Christie, at th*\niime commander of submarine* in the\n7th fleet, i* now commandant, Puget\nSound navy yard. Bremerton. Wash.\nThe prisoners were from the Jap\nanese ship Rakuyo Maru which, it\ndeveloped when the vessel was tor\npedoed. was carrying some 1400 pri\u00bb-\noners from Singapore tn Japan. The\nother prisoners presumably perished\nsince the Japanese were observed\nthreatening with pistols those who\nsought to get aboard other Japanese\nships.\nThe navy did not disclose the date\nof the Incident, but British protest*\nover Japanese treatment of prisoner*\nhave indicated that, rhe Rakuyo Maru\nwas sunk in September or October of\nlast year.\nThe Growler was reported overdu*\nand presumed lost last February 1\nand her commanding officer. Comdr\nThomas B. Oakley Jr., of Los An\ngeles is listed as missing in action.\nIt was night, with a rising moon,\nwhen the Growler pushed on the sur\nface into \u2019he midst of the convoy. A\ndestroyer swung toward her with th*\napparent intention of ramming and\nthe Growler let fly with torpedoe*.\n\"The destroyer exploded violently,\nbut beautifully, amidships.'' Oakley\nrecorded. The navy account con\ntinued:\u2014\n\"Now shells from the enemy es\ncorts fell around the Growler as she\nfired on two freighters. Th*\nGrowler continued to move in for th*\nattack despite the gunfire. In\na few minutes torpedoes from the\nGrowler hit two freighters. On one\nthere w-as an explosion. On the other\ncolumns of smoke could be observed\nbetween the bridge and the stack.\n\u201cEnemy patrol craft spotted the\nGrowler and gave chase. Th*\nGrowler fired on another enemy de\nstroyer and heard the hits register.\nOther enemy craft moved in to depth\ncharge the Growler and for several\nminutes her men could hear a serie*\nof explosions Later they reported\ntheir larget. \u2019he destroyer, was break\ning up and sinking The Growler then\nwithdrew from the area.\"\nAttacking at the same time, th*\nsubmarine Seaiion. under Comdr Eli\nT. Reich of Elmhurst, L. L. N. Y\u00ab\nsank a tanker and the Rakuyo Maru.\nThe following night the submarine\nPampanito. under Comdr Paul E.\nSummers of Lexington. Tenn., tor\npedoed four more freighters of the\nconvoy.\nTwo days later, patrolmg m the\nsame vicinity, the Pampanito found a\nraft with 15 survivors of the prison\ners who had been on the sunken Jap\nanese ship. It radioed other subma\nrines for help and. continuing *it*\nsearch, eventually picked up 75 Ra\nkayo Maru survivors. The Selaio\u00ae\npicked up 54.\nTwo other submarines, the Barb\nand the Queenfish, also received the\nPampanito s request tor help. On the\nway to the scene, they came across\nanother enemy convoy. The Barb\ngot a tanker and the aircraft carrier\nand \u2019he Queenfish sank a transport.\nThe Brab rescued 14 survivor* of\nthe Ryuko Maru and the Queenftsh\nIS. A typhoon struck and they found\nno more.\nThe Sea Lon. Barb and Queenfisll\nwere awarded presidential unit cits*\n\u2019ions for their parts in the rescue*.\nCIO TO CONDUCT\nEDUCATION DRIVE\nHillman Announces Program\nDesigned to Reach Public\n\\X ith Message About Social\nLegislation\nNew York. Aug 13\u2014(AP)\u2014Sidney\nHillman chairman of the CIO politi\ncal action committee today an\nnounced a nanonal CIO education\ncampaign for a 65-centa-an-hong\nminimum wage and $25 weekly un\nemployment compensation.\nHe said the program also seek*\npassage of the Murray-Patman full\nemployment bill. h\u00ab Murray- Wagner-\nDingell social security measure, es\ntablishment of a permanent fair em\nployment practices commission and\nnational housing program.\nDeclaring \u2019hat \"probably about 10,-\n000.000 people' would be unemployed\nin six to eight weeks Hilimar said\nar a press conference that \"we are\nin quite the same kind of eme-gency\nas in 1933 addina 'We cannot\ntolerate \u2019he possibility that our men\nered themselves with\nglory on distan\u2019 battlefields in the\nfight to preserve freedom and democ\nracy might face the prospect of re\nturning to the humiliation of app\u2019.**\nselling or leaf-raking on i dole.\u201d\nThe program, he said, will 'not cost\nmuch at all and will be \"for the good\nof labor organized and unorganized.\nan>i for the good as well of the farm\ner. the professional worker, the busi\nnessman the housewife and the zun\ne: i consumer It will be carried\non through mass meetings. leaflets,\npamphlets and the press by S.OOO 000\nCIO members.\" he said.\nWashing m Aug. 13\u2014The CIO will\nsend a delegation to visit the Soviet\nUnion at a very early date.\u201d Presi\ndent Philip Murray reported today.\nbe proclaimed by the President. But\nCongress, by a concurrent resolution,\ncould end the drafting of men. And\nsome members of Congress, now tn\nrecess, made it clear that they will\nmove to halt inductions when they\nreturn October 8. as scheduled, or\nearlier if they should be called back.\nThe general feeling u> the Senate\nand House, however, has been that\nnothing should be done qntll the war\ndefinitely ends. Meanwhile, selective\nservice was continuing Its Inductions\nat a rate of 100.600 a month.\nA proclamation that hostilities have\nbeen terminated might well be omitted\nby President Truman when Japan\ngives up. since inclusion of it would\nautomatically end selective service,\nand an army of occupation still\nwould be needed,\na","height":"25959","width":"19270"}}
